Coding plan:
"### File Structure
```
VirtualMuseum/
│
├── app.py
├── requirements.txt
├── README.md
│
├── templates/
│   ├── dashboard.html
│   ├── artifact_catalog.html
│   ├── exhibitions.html
│   ├── exhibition_details.html
│   ├── visitor_tickets.html
│   ├── virtual_events.html
│   └── audio_guides.html
│
├── static/
│   ├── css/
│   │   └── styles.css
│   ├── js/
│   │   └── scripts.js
│   └── audio/
│       └── (audio guide files, if any)
│
└── data/
    ├── users.txt
    ├── galleries.txt
    ├── exhibitions.txt
    ├── artifacts.txt
    ├── audioguides.txt
    ├── tickets.txt
    ├── events.txt
    ├── event_registrations.txt
    └── collection_logs.txt
```

### File Descriptions
```
1. app.py
   - The main backend Python application file using a web framework (e.g., Flask).
   - Handles routing for all seven pages (Dashboard, Artifact Catalog, Exhibitions, Exhibition Details, Visitor Tickets, Virtual Events, Audio Guides).
   - Implements logic for reading from and writing to the local text files in the 'data' directory.
   - Manages data parsing, filtering, searching, and user interactions.
   - Coordinates navigation between pages and serves HTML templates.

2. requirements.txt
   - Lists Python dependencies required to run the application (e.g., Flask).

3. README.md
   - Provides an overview of the project, setup instructions, and usage notes.

4. templates/ (HTML files)
   - Contains HTML templates for each page, structured according to the page designs and element IDs specified.
   - Each file corresponds to one of the seven pages:
     - dashboard.html: Museum Dashboard page.
     - artifact_catalog.html: Artifact Catalog page.
     - exhibitions.html: Exhibitions page.
     - exhibition_details.html: Exhibition Details page.
     - visitor_tickets.html: Visitor Tickets page.
     - virtual_events.html: Virtual Events page.
     - audio_guides.html: Audio Guides page.

5. static/
   - css/styles.css: Stylesheet for consistent styling across all pages.
   - js/scripts.js: JavaScript for client-side interactivity, such as button actions and filtering.
   - audio/: Optional folder to store audio guide files if needed for playback.

6. data/
   - Stores all application data in text files as specified, using pipe-delimited format.
   - Files include users.txt, galleries.txt, exhibitions.txt, artifacts.txt, audioguides.txt, tickets.txt, events.txt, event_registrations.txt, and collection_logs.txt.
   - This directory is the single source of truth for all persistent data.

This structure keeps the backend logic centralized in one Python file for simplicity, while separating frontend templates and static assets for maintainability and clarity. The data directory ensures organized local storage as per the requirements.
